rangement whereby auto own\ners can secure the work necessary\non their tires.\nWash Car Often\nMud should not be permitted to\nremain on a car any longer than\nnecessary. If mud is allowed to\ndry it. is harder to get off and it\nstains the varnish. z\n.jTHg\u2019 WASHINGTON TlMifiS lha iVaiMwios Lteuly WjhVjNiiiaDAY, MAY 14, 1924,\nIE OF FORBS\nSHOWS BIG\nGAIN\nRecord-Breaking Deliveries of 1\nMArbh During\nMonth of April\nDETROIT. Mich., May\nsalon of Ford cars gnd trucks in,\nthe United States rose to 211,410\nduring April, a substantial increase\nover the record-breaking deliveries\nof Marek, the Ford Motor Company\nannounced here, today.\nAt the same time, it was stated\nthat sales of Fordson tractors, which\nhave been steadily increasing since\nthe first of the year, exceeded 12,000\nin April.\nFurther, in the highpriced car\nfield, sales of JUineoln cars. Which\nare produced. ay a division of the\nFord Motor Company, reached a\nnew monthly- record with a total\nof 762 retail deliveries. During the\nfirst four raOnthp of the present\nyear, Lincoln salkji? showed an in\ncrease of approximately S 5 per cent\nover the same pdHpd a year ago,\nthe company says.\nWhile the sales figures of the\nqpmpany graphically Illustrate the\ncbnstantly growing popularity .of\nall Ford products, they likewise pre-'\nsent an optimistic business outlook.\nA review ol the sales records\n\u20147 \u20141\nShows that for two years retail\ndeliveries of Ford cars and trucks\nin the -United States have exceeded\n100,600 a month, the company says;\nwhile for nine of the months during\nthe past year sales were well over\nthe 160,000 mark, and the big de\nmand during Match and April this\nyear carried sales for each of those\nmonths considerably over 200,000.\nDespite late sfcrihg weather in\nmany sections, the demand for Ford\nson tractors for agricultural use\ncontinues to grow, while a notice\nable inermwe in the percentage of\nFordsons. going irtto industrial ute\nis accepted ai reflating generally\n1 prosperous conditions.\nAnalysis of th* sale* reports re\nceived from it\u00ab various brinches,\nthe company says, indicates an in\ncreased volume ot tmwiness 4or May.\nFLOOR^MATS t\nFRQM OLD TUBES\nOld inner tubes shay be used for\nmany purposes. One, purpose which\nhas recently been mentioned is for\nmaking floor mats. The old tubes\nare first cut into strips by wetting\nthe rubber and cutting with an old\nrazor. The strips are then woven\nor interlaced with each, other, in\nbasket fashion. The end-strips are\nmade double width and turned\nover, and then in place.\nBrass rivets placed along the edges\nwllL improve the appearance, m\naddition to making the mat stronger.\n\u2014Automobile Digest. 1 x\n675,840 Miles in Bus\nIn nine and one-half years one\nWhite bus has carried 669,260 pas\nsengers, run 676440 miles and con\nsistently operated at a profit lor\nthe Puyallup-Tacoma Transit Com\npany of Taooma, Wash.\n'\u2014t\ni DURANT STAGES\ni NATION-WIDE\ni SALES BSGE\n$30,000 Offered as Awards\nin Big \u201cCoast-to. Coast\nEvent\nWith 130,900 in prize money at\nstake, the great Durant cout-to\ncoast race started from New York\ncity May 10 and will finish at San\n1 Francisco July 31. z\nDurant and Star motor car sales\ni men throughout the United States\nhave entered the contest. George\nDavis, yUes manager of the Harper\n\u2018Motor Company, Washington, claims\n1 th>t on ot hl m>n wtu wln the\nI\ni- I vp: HkHHwHB HMMHm\nSK amhib\nbShSHHbh|HHh\nBraMiBBB\nraj\niliq\nDURANT\nHARPER MOTOR CO., Inc.\nR. H. HARPER, Pres.\nv\n1128 Connecticut Avenue\n\nBetween L aijd M Streets\nShow Rooms Open Evenings and Sundays\u2014We Will Trade In Used Cars\nV.f\n.._\nAUTOMOBILE SALESMEN ARE NEEDED to take care of the large demand\narising from the first showing of the New DURANT. Profitable connection for-\nexperienced Salesmen. See Mr. Davis, 1128 Connecticut Avenue. j\niejH\"i'ii f. x, l wus^sszas&;B l I :.T-'gaTjK;?\"M ll ?gJsss;sa Tr;.L l, r,_.x.:.|s\u00bb'LJgsswwWMWkl\n-T\ncapital prize if he does not himself.\nThis is not a road race, but tu I\nsales race. Every gale of a new\nDurant or Star car credits the sales-\nman with so many miles on the\njourney from the Atlantic to' the\nPacific. The central office of Durant\nmotors will receive a 3 dally report\nfrom the smallest town to the great\nest 'cities where they have dealers,\nand ths progress of each will be re\ncorded on a gigantic map.\nCities are divided into four class!'\nflcations so thsjt every Durant and\nStar salesman will stand an equal\nchance to win.' There will be fifty\ncapital prises, ranging from 3100 I\nto 12,000, out of a fund of 115.000\ndonated, by W. C v Durant, president\nof Durant Motors, personally, and\nthen there will be |SOO added prizes\nfor individual salesmen and dealers.\nGold, bronze and other medals also\nwill be awarded, in addition to\nwhich the Durant motors promise j\nto advertise winners -from coast-|o\ncoast which probably will' lead to 1\nsales manager\u2019s, jobs for many of 1\nthe successful salesmen. t\nIn view of the above. Sales Man-\nager Davis, of the Harper Motor\nCompany, this city, is being flooded\nwith applications by salesmen, but\nthe \"more the merrier,\" he says.\nGSR PRICES AT\nBOTTOM, SAYS\nWILLYS\nLow Figure* Have Not Kept\nIndustry at Capacity\nStride, He Declares.\nf 4\nWy CMmopoHtck News\u2019 Mrvtee.\nNEW YORK, May 14. \u2014\u2019\u201cPrices -of\nmotor cars have touched bottom,\u201d\naccording to J.iN. Willys, president\nof the Willys Overland Company, in\nan interview with Dow Jones and\nCompany, today.\n\"Present ffiw prices,\u201d said Mr.\nWillys, \u201cwere made last year When\nmanufacturers believed a sufficient\nvolume of business could be secured\nat these levels to Insure capacity\nschedules.\n\u201cUnseasonable spring weather and.\na slight unsettlement in general bus\niness conditions have upset these\ncalculations and a number of lead\ning producers have not -been able\nto attain the contemplated schedules.\n\u201cI figure production schedUles-are\nabout three weeks in* advance ofc\ntail conditions, and factories are\nstowing up output to bring produc\ntion curve closer to sales line and\nallow stocks that have been accu\nmulated to be absorbed. As aTedult 1\noperations now are art about 80 per\ncent of the first Quarter peak,,\n.\u201cThe motor industry is, still a\nseasonal business andi it is better\nto enter the season with lar\u00a3e\nstocks ready for market than to\nfind factories loaded wi|h inven\ntories when demand normally slacks\noff.\n\"On the whole I think the pres\nent situation lb satisfactory and\nresults of the next few months\nwill be a Surprise to those who\ntake a pessimistic view of the out>\nt look.\u201d","height":"30685","width":"24615"}}
